photo.title: Ownership stamps of the library of the German province of the Jesuit order, of the Jesuit community in Cologne, Germany, and of the Fürstlich-Leiningische Bibliothek in Amorbach, Germany
photo.description: PROV. GERM. BIBL.SCRIPT. SOC.JESU [Stamp of the library of the German province of the Jesuit order. Probably to be read as "Provinciae Germaniae Bibliotheca Scriptorum Societatis Jesu" by analogy with the provenance inscription Provinciae Germaniae Bibliotheca Theologorum Societatis Jesu recorded here. CERL deals with the various permutations of German Jesuit provinces in the 20th and 21st centuries; possibly this stamp is to be dated prior to 1921, when the Niederdeutsche and Oberdeutsche Provinzen came into being (from a single Deutsche Provinz? the entry is unclear). Established heading: Jesuits. Deutsche Provinz] IHS DOM. COLON. [Stamp, with Jesuit emblems, of the Jesuit community in Cologne, Germany (founded 1544), struck through in pencil.] FÜRSTL. LEINING. HOF- BIBLIOTHEK [Stamp of the Fürstlich-Leiningische Bibliothek (or Fürstlich Leiningensche Bibliothek; the name appears to be spelled variously) at Amorbach, Germany. (Cf. another example in Wikimedia here.) After Abtei Amorbach was secularized, its buildings and library became the property of the recently created Prince of Leiningen, Carl Friedrich Wilhelm. The library remains a going concern today with some 31000 volumes, mostly concerned with family and local history, and looks gorgeous. DNB heading: Fürstlich-Leiningische Bibliothek] Penn Libraries call number: GC55 G9857 592v All images from this book

photo.title: Book label of John Penington & Son bookshop at 127 S. 7th Street in Philadelphia, PA
photo.description: Book label of John Penington & Son bookshop at 127 S. 7th Street in Philadelphia, PA. The Peningtons arrived in Pennsylvania in 1698 and were a leading and active Quaker family in Philadelphia business and politics. John Penington (1799-1867‏) and his son, Edward Penington, ran the book shop and specialized in rare and foreign books. John's father, Edward, was a bibliophile with a large personal library of over 6,000 volumes and was a prominent businessman in the city as a sugar refiner and merchant. Cf. the Penington Family Papers at the Historical Society of Pennsylvania. Established heading: John Penington & Son Established heading: Penington, John, 1799-1867 Penn Libraries call number: IC55 T1856 582m

photo.title: Stamp of the Fürstlich Thurn und Taxissche Hofbibliothek
photo.description: Fürstlich Thurn und Taxische Hofbibliothek Regensburg Stamp of the Fürstlich Thurn und Taxissche Hofbibliothek in Regensburg, Germany. In origin the private library of Alexander Ferdinand, Fürst zu Thurn und Taxis (1704-1773), it was expanded by his son Carl Anselm (1733-1805) under the direction of Baron Franz Ludwig von Berberich. In 1812 the library moved with its owners into the former Reichstift St. Emmeram, a Benedictine monastery secularized in 1810, subsequently known as Schloss Thurn und Taxis. (The monastic library itself had previously been removed to Munich.) It is known today as the Fürst Thurn und Taxis Hofbibliothek und Zentralarchiv. Established heading: Fürstlich Thurn und Taxissche Hofbibliothek Penn Libraries call number: GC55 F4329 578n All images from this book
